It's that type of, well, we have to make an S1 as a registration statement.

31:04.460 --> 31:06.620
You send it to the SEC.

31:06.620 --> 31:07.620
They read it.

31:07.620 --> 31:08.620
They ask you questions.

31:08.620 --> 31:09.620
They ask you to make changes.

31:09.620 --> 31:10.620
You send it back.

31:10.620 --> 31:11.620
They read it.

31:11.620 --> 31:13.260
So on and so forth.

31:13.260 --> 31:21.980
And then you can sell, generally, shares to the public or other financial instruments, which

31:21.980 --> 31:22.980
generally shares.

31:22.980 --> 31:27.100
And then you have a whole bunch of ongoing reporting requirements.

31:27.100 --> 31:31.020
When do you have to file financial statements with the SEC?

31:31.020 --> 31:33.820
What things do you need to disclose?

31:33.820 --> 31:35.620
What are your officers doing?

31:35.620 --> 31:37.740
Are they buying or selling shares?

31:37.740 --> 31:38.940
When are they trading?

31:38.940 --> 31:41.340
When are they not trading?

31:41.340 --> 31:44.940
All of these things are actually pretty good things.

31:44.940 --> 31:59.820
But, they are things that are hard to do in a natively crypto context.

31:59.820 --> 32:05.180
But they're also expensive.

32:05.180 --> 32:11.820
Even for a fairly small company preparing to file, or do a registration, will be a seven

32:11.820 --> 32:16.780
figure cost and probably seven figures of annual compliance.

32:16.780 --> 32:27.220
And so you can't really be a person who wants to run a half million dollar common enterprise

32:27.220 --> 32:29.420
and practically speaking, file.

32:29.420 --> 32:33.500
So they say, well, okay,

32:33.500 --> 32:34.500
we have a solution for that,

32:34.500 --> 32:38.020
that's the crowdfunding exemption,

32:38.020 --> 32:39.500
and this is Reg A.

32:39.500 --> 32:46.980
Reg A is the exemptions to registration.

32:46.980 --> 33:01.300
But there was a specific one done for crowdfunding.

33:01.300 --> 33:13.180
You can do effectively a light form of registration if you're crowdfunding within certain hurdles,

33:13.180 --> 33:17.340
20 million and 75 million respectively.

33:17.340 --> 33:25.260
And so you don't have to go through the whole full regulatory regime of being a public company

33:25.260 --> 33:27.820
like Google.

33:27.820 --> 33:31.420
You do have some reporting requirements, you can't just go out there and put your hand

33:31.420 --> 33:32.420
up and say, hey, look, I'm crowdfunding,

33:32.420 --> 33:33.420
I don't have to do anything.

33:33.420 --> 33:35.660
That's not how it works.

33:35.660 --> 33:36.820
But it's a lighter form,

33:36.820 --> 33:40.060
it's a significantly lighter registration form.

33:40.060 --> 33:55.620
So, practically speaking, if something is a security, you can sell it using one of three

33:55.620 --> 34:06.020
ways. One, to Acredited Investors and Qualified Purchasers. Two, to the public, host registration.

34:06.020 --> 34:14.340
Three, to the public under the crowdfunding exemptions, but within certain limits on how

34:14.340 --> 34:18.500
much you can raise.

34:18.500 --> 34:23.700
These are, or if it's not a security, you don't have to do any of these things, but then it

34:23.700 --> 34:31.580
really has to not be a security.

34:31.580 --> 34:37.060
On this section, this is what I would like you to remember.

34:37.060 --> 34:45.460
The Howey Test and these three models for securities, Acredited Investors, registration,

34:45.460 --> 34:47.660
Reg A crowdfunding exemptions.

34:47.660 --> 34:54.660
Now, how does this translate to real life?

34:54.660 --> 34:57.660
How does this translate to what people do?

34:57.660 --> 35:09.460
Well, the primary model for financing technology startups, remains venture capital firms.

35:09.460 --> 35:13.020
What are venture capital firms?

35:13.020 --> 35:25.500
Venture capital firms are investment funds who have a general partner who is a company,

35:25.500 --> 35:33.740
but you can think of it as the people running the fund, and limited partners, who are the

35:33.740 --> 35:34.740
investors.

35:34.740 --> 35:40.380
The investors and venture capital funds are Accredited Investors or Qualified Purchasers

35:40.380 --> 35:45.020
because units of a venture capital fund are definitely securities.

35:45.020 --> 35:49.540
And who are these famous institutional investors?

35:49.540 --> 36:03.900
Well, interestingly, the largest institutional investors in the world are pension funds.

36:03.900 --> 36:09.900
So, it's kind of funny that like, when you think of institutional investors and they're very big

36:09.900 --> 36:18.260
and not like a common person, it's primarily the retirement savings of school teachers

36:18.260 --> 36:25.180
and firefighters that have been aggregated, but because they have been aggregated, a very large

36:25.180 --> 36:30.260
number, will then have people managing those retirement savings.

36:30.260 --> 36:38.980
A one of the things those people do is invest those retirement savings into venture capital

36:38.980 --> 36:45.980
funds will then go and invest in the service.

36:45.980 --> 37:02.020
Other buckets of typical investors, sovereign wealth funds, some corporate treasurers, family

37:02.020 --> 37:11.300
offices, which is just a fancy word for effectively, an investment team for a really, really rich

37:11.300 --> 37:12.300
family.

37:12.300 --> 37:16.660
An ultra high net worth or a high net worth individuals.

37:16.660 --> 37:20.460
But really the biggest investor in venture capital funds tends to be pension funds,

37:20.460 --> 37:23.860
they have more money than any of these people.

37:23.860 --> 37:38.340
So VCs are both allowed to invest in unregistered securities and also have the orientation skill,

37:38.340 --> 37:46.020
mental desire to invest in technology startups.

37:46.020 --> 37:58.340
The... most of the, pretty much all of the infrastructure firms in NFT space, all of the gaming firms

37:58.340 --> 38:05.860
in NFT space, many of the metaverse firms in NFT space and some of the project teams

38:05.860 --> 38:15.940
in the NFT space, Yuga, dual, etc etc, have raised money from venture capital funds.

38:15.940 --> 38:18.300
Why?

38:18.300 --> 38:25.860
Because it is safe, easy and fast.

38:25.860 --> 38:34.900
Venture capital firms can make a decision fairly quickly, and by making that decision,

38:34.900 --> 38:41.380
they can write a cheque, for $2, $5, $10, $20 million.

38:41.380 --> 38:45.540
You do not, you can sell them normal equity,

38:45.540 --> 38:54.740
you don't have to go through any complicated convolutions of designing some unique instrument

38:54.740 --> 38:56.740
to make sure that it's not a security.

38:56.740 --> 39:06.300
You know, say, look, you can buy shares in our company and you, the entrepreneur, don't

39:06.300 --> 39:11.660
have to worry about any regulatory risk.

39:11.660 --> 39:23.300
They're very much allowed to buy shares in your company, and this practical aspect tends

39:23.300 --> 39:29.340
to be fairly dominant in how these firms are financed because most of the other ways

39:29.340 --> 39:34.540
you can do it, are actually pretty complicated.

39:34.540 --> 39:46.220
You're certainly, you're certainly not going to go registered to go public as a startup,

39:46.220 --> 39:47.220
right?

39:47.220 --> 39:50.420
You don't have the capacity or the money, you're not right, mature enough.

39:50.420 --> 39:57.420
So this tends to be if you're going to sell a security, a very easy and fast way to do

39:57.420 --> 39:58.420
it.

39:58.420 --> 40:00.620
What else are we seeing?

40:00.620 --> 40:09.900
Well, we see DAOs and DAOs is one of my pet peeves in the space because DAO literally

40:09.900 --> 40:12.540
means something very different.

40:12.540 --> 40:19.900
It says it right there in its name, Decentralized Autonomous Organization.

40:19.900 --> 40:27.620
DAOs were meant to be something like smart contracts that engaged in economic activity.

40:27.620 --> 40:35.380
They were actually decentralized and autonomous when first thought of in this way.

40:35.380 --> 40:39.060
Today people use the word now very differently.

40:39.060 --> 40:43.380
They use it as a group of people doing something.

40:43.380 --> 40:52.180
A group of people doing something is neither decentralized nor is it autonomous.

40:52.180 --> 40:58.900
It is, a group of people doing something.

40:58.900 --> 41:05.700
And when you have a group of people doing something, if they're not careful, one of the

41:05.700 --> 41:11.900
things they will discover they are doing, is selling unregistered securities to people.

41:11.900 --> 41:19.940
So my conceptual problems with the way that terms are being used aside, what do we see

41:19.940 --> 41:23.100
in terms of DAOs in the NFT space?

41:23.100 --> 41:33.500
Well, we see DAOs that are effectively correctly legally organized and compliant.

41:33.500 --> 41:40.540
These DAOs usually have registered a company, an LLC.

41:40.540 --> 41:51.860
They usually KYC check the information and write down your name and social security number

41:51.860 --> 41:55.700
and address of everyone investing.

41:55.700 --> 42:05.740
And they ask them to provide documentation or self-certification that they are accredited

42:05.740 --> 42:06.740
investors.

42:06.740 --> 42:13.260
A good example of this is Flamingo DAO.

42:13.260 --> 42:15.900
Flamingo DAO does all these things.

42:15.900 --> 42:23.740
It is a DAO, they call themselves a DAO, but effectively they're a company.

42:23.740 --> 42:34.740
And effectively they comply with similar hurdles for their members as venture capital funders.

42:34.740 --> 42:40.020
There are some differences in how they make decisions.

42:40.020 --> 42:47.100
All the down members can contribute to decisions, where the venture capital fund investors typically

42:47.100 --> 42:49.980
do not contribute to the decisions.

42:49.980 --> 42:57.100
But from a legal financial infrastructure perspective, it's very, very similar.

42:57.100 --> 43:07.500
Then there's what the NFT projects tend to call DAOs, which are all over the map, very

43:07.500 --> 43:10.500
poorly organized.

43:10.500 --> 43:15.900
I think in many cases very poorly thought out.

43:15.900 --> 43:28.940
And some of them are going to get in trouble because they are in fact, the type of activity

43:28.940 --> 43:32.620
that really should only be opened under US law, without judging whether it's right or

43:32.620 --> 43:39.180
wrong, to Accredited Investors and they're not limiting to Accredited Investors.

43:39.180 --> 43:51.060
And some of them are not going to get in trouble with the SEC in any way, but are kind of lying

43:51.060 --> 43:53.500
to the members.

43:53.500 --> 44:03.580
You know, you see DAOs of the type that say, oh, you're a DAO, and you're in the DAO if you own the

44:03.580 --> 44:04.740
projects NFTs.

44:04.740 --> 44:11.460
But the equity is owned by someone else, the governance of that equity is owned by someone

44:11.460 --> 44:14.660
else, the decisions are all made by someone else

44:14.660 --> 44:20.940
and sure, there's a DAO council and they'll ask the people their opinions here or there.

44:20.940 --> 44:27.420
Well, I mean, that's no different than having a customer advisory board.

44:27.420 --> 44:34.500
It's just if you told people, if you bought this NFT, you're part of our customer advisory

44:34.500 --> 44:38.860
board or community advisory board.

44:38.860 --> 44:44.300
It doesn't sound as appealing as being part of the DAO.

44:44.300 --> 44:51.260
And so what's going on there is I think they're misleading people for people to attribute more

44:51.260 --> 44:55.340
value to their token.

44:55.340 --> 44:59.020
And it's not great.

44:59.020 --> 45:09.060
I think it's going to be very hard for most non-legally organized DAOs to operate in a

45:09.060 --> 45:12.580
compliant manner the way they're doing it.

45:12.580 --> 45:17.340
I'm not going to judge any specific project.

45:17.340 --> 45:20.900
I don't know all the facts of an expert projects.

45:20.900 --> 45:28.780
But I believe there's certain quote unquote DAOs operating in the space that effectively, are

45:28.780 --> 45:30.820
violating security law.

45:30.820 --> 45:37.980
They might not be doing it on purpose, but they are effectively doing it.

45:37.980 --> 45:39.540
Well, Token Offerings.

45:39.540 --> 45:48.140
This is a very big deal in the quote unquote ICO era of 2017-2018, where everyone and their

45:48.140 --> 45:55.180
brother, mother, sister, parent was going around saying, well, we're going to do ICO.

45:55.180 --> 45:58.260
We're going to sell you this token,

45:58.260 --> 46:00.660
it will fund our operation, 

46:00.660 --> 46:12.300
and we're going to make the "X for Y", the token for doctors to organize their medical practices,

46:12.300 --> 46:15.380
or what have you.

46:15.380 --> 46:22.820
The reality is the vast majority of these ICOs were actually securities,

46:22.820 --> 46:30.540
and eventually the SEC cracked down on them,

46:30.540 --> 46:35.500
and people stopped doing it because they don't want to get in trouble.

46:35.500 --> 46:46.500
I believe a typical fungible token ICO is very hard to do as a not a security.

46:46.500 --> 46:55.140
Or if I want to be more precise, it is very hard to make it not a security, but also achieve

46:55.140 --> 47:05.340
the objectives that the organizer of the token is likely trying to achieve.

47:05.340 --> 47:08.780
What do I mean by that?

47:08.780 --> 47:23.020
Well, most of the time people who are doing an ICO are trying to raise money to do something.

47:23.020 --> 47:24.020
They have an idea.

47:24.020 --> 47:30.020
They woke up one morning and said, oh, I want to do, execute this idea,

47:30.020 --> 47:35.220
I know I need a team to do it and in order to get that team, I need money to hire that

47:35.220 --> 47:40.580
team and to do marketing and what have you.

47:40.580 --> 47:51.180
And because of this, I need to raise money.

47:51.180 --> 48:00.260
The reality is most things of that genre are going to end up meeting the Howey Test.

48:00.260 --> 48:06.940
You're going to sell the token to people who are going to buy it with an expectation

48:06.940 --> 48:07.940
of profit.

48:07.940 --> 48:11.260
It's definitely an investment of money.

48:11.260 --> 48:15.220
There's almost certainly a common enterprise.

48:15.220 --> 48:24.900
And, it is most likely reliant on the efforts of others, namely you.

48:24.900 --> 48:38.140
And so the issue here is you can make a token offering that is not a security,

48:38.140 --> 48:41.180
it's just unlikely that you want to.

48:41.180 --> 48:48.460
But that's usually where the problem was, not that it's impossible to do it.

48:48.460 --> 48:53.420
It's just that once you do it, it's not likely to meet your objectives because your objectives

48:53.420 --> 48:56.700
usually work.

48:56.700 --> 49:03.660
Of the... in the genre of, I want to build something and I need money to build something and I'm

49:03.660 --> 49:08.740
the person who's going to build that thing that I'm trying to build,

49:08.740 --> 49:18.900
and that ends up generally likely not being sufficiently decentralized to not be a security.

49:18.900 --> 49:24.780
So I'm skeptical of most token offerings not being securities.

49:24.780 --> 49:28.980
Now, NFT sales, this is new.

49:28.980 --> 49:30.060
This is very interesting,

49:30.060 --> 49:36.380
and I suspect there is a little bit more fertile ground here to do it correctly while

49:36.380 --> 49:43.980
also, plenty of pitfalls to do it incorrectly.

49:43.980 --> 49:48.260
People can sell NFTs, which is underlying there's a form of token.

49:48.260 --> 49:50.340
And do all types of things.

49:50.340 --> 49:51.900
It could be a piece of work;

49:51.900 --> 49:52.900
I'm an NFT photographer,
49:52.900 --> 49:54.860
I sold a piece of work.

49:54.860 --> 49:59.500
It could be a PFP, then a PFP process.

49:59.500 --> 50:04.700
It could be a token that gives you some type of utility in a game or application,

50:04.700 --> 50:07.940
there are many reasons.

50:07.940 --> 50:15.580
Generally, if it's this type of thing like I just described, but they are buying something

50:15.580 --> 50:19.540
and that thing that they're buying is an object,

50:19.540 --> 50:24.860
but if it was sold pre tokens, I went to the gallery,

50:24.860 --> 50:30.540
I bought a painting.

50:30.540 --> 50:35.220
I went to the real estate agent, I bought a piece of land.

50:35.220 --> 50:41.100
These things are not securities.

50:41.100 --> 50:43.620
These things are perfectly fine as financing methods.

50:43.620 --> 50:49.900
These things are income or revenue to the person selling them to you,

50:49.900 --> 50:54.260
and they're not a financial instrument, right?

50:54.260 --> 50:57.220
Where people get in trouble though, and how I think people are going to get in trouble

50:57.220 --> 50:59.220
with NFts is,

50:59.220 --> 51:06.340
they say, oh, yeah, you buy this cool NFT,

51:06.340 --> 51:17.460
and it's in the, it will have a share of the project DAO and the project DAO is going

51:17.460 --> 51:27.540
to get 50% of the royalties from all the trades that happen later with the NFTs

51:27.540 --> 51:33.980
and also 10% of the primary sales of future NFTs so that DAO is going to be valuable and

51:33.980 --> 51:35.780
you'll have a share of the Dow,

51:35.780 --> 51:36.780
well, congratulations,

51:36.780 --> 51:40.660
you've made a security.

51:40.660 --> 51:45.060
The real life equivalent would be you go to a gallery and you say, and the gallery is

51:45.060 --> 51:46.900
like, oh, I'm going to sell you this painting,

51:46.900 --> 51:52.020
and when you buy this painting and have a really beautiful painting, it's by G. Taring.

51:52.020 --> 51:57.340
and also, I am going to give you one 10,000th of the profit of my gallery for the rest of

51:57.340 --> 52:00.620
eternity.

52:00.620 --> 52:05.700
That part that I'm going to give you one 10,000th of my profit of my gallery for the rest of

52:05.700 --> 52:17.940
eternity, that part turns that key card in painting into security.

52:17.940 --> 52:21.100
We don't have case law in this area yet.

52:21.100 --> 52:27.460
There hasn't been enforcement in this area yet.

52:27.460 --> 52:32.740
I do think that though, both of these statements are going to be true.

52:32.740 --> 52:40.620
I think there's a lot of opportunities to have effectively community based funding that

52:40.620 --> 52:50.020
is not a security in a way that is hard to do with fungible tokens because you can solve

52:50.020 --> 52:54.060
something that has value in and of itself, whereas a fungible token,

52:54.060 --> 52:57.660
it's very hard to have value in and of itself.

52:57.660 --> 53:07.460
If XCOPY, they did an example, wants to do all types of projects in the NFT field,

53:07.460 --> 53:19.860
and XCOPY sells a piece of one of one art for 100 ETH or 666 thrusters for however

53:19.860 --> 53:27.260
specific result or an open edition for one ETH.

53:27.260 --> 53:28.260
This is fine.

53:28.260 --> 53:34.180
None of these things are securities.

53:34.180 --> 53:36.380
XCOPY will have earned a lot of money.

53:36.380 --> 53:46.780
It will have been given to XCOPY by people who broadly believe in the XCOPY brand, universe,

53:46.780 --> 53:47.780
etc.

53:47.780 --> 53:52.980
They might even be expecting a profit, but they're not going to call an enterprise with XCOPY.

53:52.980 --> 53:55.260
They own an XCOPY painting.

53:55.260 --> 54:00.340
XCOPY is off to go do something else, they're not going to call an enterprise together.

54:00.340 --> 54:07.340
So, I believe this ability to reach out to your community, customers, fans, whatever you

54:07.340 --> 54:13.340
want to call them, and sell them tokens directly that are, in this case, non-fungible, is a

54:13.340 --> 54:17.940
viable fundraising method here.

54:17.940 --> 54:21.860
I also believe quite a few people are going to screw it up.

54:21.860 --> 54:29.100
They are going to accidentally create securities or in some cases on purpose, but I think in

54:29.100 --> 54:39.820
most cases, accidentally, and they will have some enforcement in a couple years against some

54:39.820 --> 54:42.020
of these accidental ones.

54:42.020 --> 54:46.900
They're not going to be able to chase around all of them because there's a lot of them,

54:46.900 --> 54:49.460
but they don't generally need to chase around a lot of them,

54:49.460 --> 54:52.260
they just go after a handful of them.

54:52.260 --> 54:57.700
And what happened last year was, they went after a handful of them and then everyone got worried and

54:57.700 --> 55:04.100
there was less, there was less, fewer ICOs after them.

55:04.100 --> 55:12.660
And so, to me, this is the most interesting and new area in the financing space.

55:12.660 --> 55:18.380
Is there a way to use NFTs or, what are the ways to use NFTs in a compliant manner?

55:18.380 --> 55:21.580
They went, I don't believe in all these things.

55:21.580 --> 55:25.220
I get it, I get it, and the rules should change.

55:25.220 --> 55:31.020
Yeah, I actually think the Howey Test needs to be updated or the Acreditor Investor rules

55:31.020 --> 55:36.860
need to be updated to account for the types of Web3 projects we're seeing.

55:36.860 --> 55:43.340
I do not believe that if you're spending points to ETH and you get part of the royalties

55:43.340 --> 55:49.500
of an NFT DAO, you actually need to have a million dollars in net worth to be able to do it.

55:49.500 --> 55:54.020
But that's going to involve changing the regulations of the United States and I don't

55:54.020 --> 55:56.220
think it's going to happen imminently.

55:56.220 --> 55:58.820
It maybe will happen in a few years, but it's not the case today.

